Q1:

Recall the advertising data from the last activity; you showed that there was an interaction between age and product type.

A large advertising firm specializes in creating television commercials for childrenâs products. The firm wants to design a study to investigate factors that may affect the lengths of time a commercial is able to hold a childâs attention. A preliminary study determines that two factors that may be important are the age of the child and the type of product being advertised. The firm wants to determine whether there were large differences in the mean length of time that the commercial is able to hold the childâs attention depending on these two factors. If there proves to be a difference, the firm would then attempt to determine new types of commercials depending on the product and targeted age group.

# clear environment
rm(list = ls())

# extract data
data <- as_tibble(gsheet2tbl("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/16_HOSmIBDD9oYY1oBQ5Df6eFH9nT6GgO1UWcbMZNLUo/edit?usp=sharing"))

# transform data
clean_data <- data %>% 
  # delete empty rows
  drop_na() %>%
  rename("cereal_5-6" = "A1-P1") %>% 
  rename("cereal_7-8" = "A2-P1") %>% 
  rename("cereal_9-10" = "A3-P1") %>% 
  rename("games_5-6" = "A1-P2") %>% 
  rename("games_7-8" = "A2-P2") %>% 
  rename("games_9-10" = "A3-P2")

# pivot to long data
prelong_data <- clean_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("cereal_5-6", "cereal_7-8", "cereal_9-10", "games_5-6", "games_7-8", "games_9-10"),
               names_to = "product_&_age",
               values_to = "Results")

# separate product and age into independent columns
separate_data <- prelong_data %>% 
  separate(`product_&_age`, into = c("Product", "Age"), sep = "_")
  
# remove Child column
long_data <- within(separate_data, rm(Child)) 
# interaction plot: Product, Age
interaction.plot(long_data$Product, long_data$Age, long_data$Results)

  1. Construct the profile plot for this data.
# Two-way interaction plot: Age, Product
interaction.plot(x.factor = long_data$Age, trace.factor = long_data$Product, response = long_data$Results, 
                 fun = mean, 
                 type = "b", legend = TRUE, 
                 xlab = "Age", ylab="Product",
                 pch=c(1,19), col = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800"))

# profile plot using ggline
profile <- ggline(long_data, x = "Age", y = "Results", color = "Product",
       add = "mean",
       show.line.label = TRUE,
       label.rectangle = TRUE,
       palette = c("gray", "magenta"),
       ylab = "Product")
profile_plot <- ggpar(profile, ylim = c(15, 50))
profile_plot

  1. (Challenge!) Perform Tukeyâs test to determine which treatment groups are significantly different. Test at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level.
# Two-way ANOVA
# Null Hypothesis:
# - H1: The means of observations grouped by Product are the same
# - H2: The means of observations grouped by Age are the same
# - H3: There is no interaction between Product and Age

summary(h1_h2 <- aov(long_data$Results ~ factor(long_data$Product) + factor(long_data$Age)))
                          Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
factor(long_data$Product)  1   2018  2018.4  12.117 0.000976 ***
factor(long_data$Age)      2   1303   651.5   3.911 0.025705 *  
Residuals                 56   9328   166.6                     
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Product
TukeyHSD(h1_h2, "factor(long_data$Product)")
  Tukey multiple comparisons of means
    95% family-wise confidence level

Fit: aov(formula = long_data$Results ~ factor(long_data$Product) + factor(long_data$Age))

$`factor(long_data$Product)`
             diff      lwr      upr     p adj
games-cereal 11.6 4.924332 18.27567 0.0009757

Tukeyâs Test for Product

There is sufficient evidence at the \(\alpha = 0.05\) level to suggest that the means of observations grouped by cereal and video games are different.

# Age
TukeyHSD(h1_h2, "factor(long_data$Age)")
  Tukey multiple comparisons of means
    95% family-wise confidence level

Fit: aov(formula = long_data$Results ~ factor(long_data$Product) + factor(long_data$Age))

$`factor(long_data$Age)`
          diff        lwr      upr     p adj
7-8-5-6   2.05 -7.7761856 11.87619 0.8705131
9-10-5-6 10.75  0.9238144 20.57619 0.0289003
9-10-7-8  8.70 -1.1261856 18.52619 0.0925938
plot(TukeyHSD(h1_h2, "factor(long_data$Age)"))

Tukeyâs Test for Age groups

There is sufficient evidence at the \(\alpha = 0.05\) level to suggest that the means of observations grouped by age are different. Furthermore, the main difference is between the ages of (5 to 6) and (9 to 10).

  1. Write a short paragraph to explain your results to the advertising researchers.

Conclusion

The kids spent more attention to advertisements for video games between the ages of 9 to 10.

  1. Graphically assess the ANOVA assumptions â is ANOVA appropriate here?

It is not appropriate to use ANOVA assumptions for this case. Visually, the data does not meet normality.

h3 <- aov(long_data$Results ~ long_data$Product * factor(long_data$Age))
plot(h3)

Q2:

Recall the tomato data from the last activity; you showed that there was not an interaction between shading and phase of growth and that there was at least one main effect.

A horticulturalist at a large research institution designs a study to evaluate the effect on tomato yields of water loss due to transpiration. She decides to examine four levels of shading of the tomato plants at three stages of the tomato plantâs development. The four levels of shading (0, 25%, 50%, and 75%) were selected to reduce the solar exposure of the plants. The shading remained in place for 20 days during the early, middle, and late phases of the tomato plantsâ growth. There were four plots of tomatoes randomly assigned to each of the combinations of shading and growth stage. At the end of the study, the yields per plot in pounds were recorded. The data are given here: Google Sheet.

# clear environment
rm(list = ls())

# extract data
data <- as_tibble(gsheet2tbl("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1kUxXje3cTl_PZFQcg8FvESo34UuGNwm1GrKGc4HN0_A/edit?usp=sharing"))

# transform data
clean_data <- data %>% 
  # delete empty rows
  drop_na()
  1. (Challenge!) Construct the profile plot for this data.
# Two-way interaction plot: Shade, Phase
interaction.plot(x.factor = clean_data$PctShade, trace.factor = clean_data$Phase, response = clean_data$Yield, 
                 fun = mean, 
                 type = "b", legend = TRUE)

# profile plot using ggline: Shade, Phase
profile <- ggline(clean_data, x = "PctShade", y = "Yield", color = "Phase",
       add = "mean",
       show.line.label = TRUE,
       label.rectangle = FALSE,
       palette = c("grey", "grey", "magenta"),
       xlab = "Levels of Shading",
       ylab = "Yield")
profile_plot <- ggpar(profile, ylim = c(45, 70))
profile_plot

  1. If there is a main effect of shading, perform Tukeyâs test to determine which levels of shading are significantly different. Test at the \(\alpha=0.10\) level.
# Two-way ANOVA
# Null Hypothesis:
# - H1: The means of observations grouped by Shade are the same
# - H2: The means of observations grouped by Phase are the same
# - H3: There is no interaction between Shade and Phase

summary(h1_h2 <- aov(clean_data$Yield ~ factor(clean_data$PctShade) + factor(clean_data$Phase)))
                            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
factor(clean_data$PctShade)  3     84   28.04   0.278 0.8407  
factor(clean_data$Phase)     2    513  256.56   2.546 0.0932 .
Residuals                   34   3426  100.77                 
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Shade
TukeyHSD(h1_h2, "factor(clean_data$PctShade)", conf.level = 0.90)
  Tukey multiple comparisons of means
    90% family-wise confidence level

Fit: aov(formula = clean_data$Yield ~ factor(clean_data$PctShade) + factor(clean_data$Phase))

75-25  3.9211111  -7.063401 14.90562 0.8300822
75-50  1.7800000  -8.911539 12.47154 0.9785309

Tukeyâs Test for Levels of Shading

There is sufficient evidence at the \(\alpha\)=0.10 level to suggest that the means of observations grouped by levels of shading are the same.

  1. If there is a main effect of phase of growth, perform Tukeyâs test to determine which phases of growth are significantly different. Test at the \(\alpha=0.10\) level.
# Phase
TukeyHSD(h1_h2, "factor(clean_data$Phase)", conf.level = 0.90)
  Tukey multiple comparisons of means

Tukeyâs Test for Phases of Growth

There is sufficient evidence at the \(\alpha\)=0.10 level to suggest a main effect between Early and Late phase.

  1. Write a short paragraph to explain your results to the horticulturist.

Conclusion

Our findings suggest that the best performance of tomato yields of water loss due to transpiration is a 75% shade level in the middle growth phase.

  1. Graphically assess the ANOVA assumptions â is ANOVA appropriate here?
